How It Works

The architecture is designed with independent processor instances, allowing you to run different tools concurrently:

✅ Supported Concurrent Combinations:

- SKU Tester + PSLP Tester
- Banner Tester + Mix-In Ad Tester
- SKU Tester + Banner Tester + PSLP Tester (all 3 at once!)
- Any combination of different tools

❌ Not Allowed:

- Two SKU tests at the same time (same tool instance)
- Two Banner tests at the same time (same tool instance)
- Two PSLP tests at the same time (same tool instance)

Why This Works

Each processor has completely independent resources:

// Each processor singleton has its own:

- browser instance (Playwright browser)
- context and page
- isRunning state flag
- results array
- event emitter

The Code:
// server.js - Line 309-311
if (skuProcessor.getStatus().isRunning) {
return res.status(409).json({ error: 'SKU capture already in progress' });
}
This only prevents running the same processor twice, not different processors.

Resource Considerations

When running multiple tools concurrently:

Pros:

- ✅ Faster overall execution (parallel processing)
- ✅ No conflicts between processors
- ✅ Each tool progresses independently

Cons:

- ⚠️ Higher memory usage (each browser instance uses ~100-200MB)
- ⚠️ Higher CPU usage (multiple Playwright instances)
- ⚠️ Multiple browser windows open simultaneously

Testing Concurrent Execution

You can test this right now:

1. Start SKU Tester with a few SKUs
2. While it's running, navigate to PSLP Tester
3. Start PSLP test - it will run alongside the SKU test
4. Both will report progress via WebSocket independently

Current Implementation Details

Each processor tracks its own state:
// processors/base-processor.js
class BaseProcessor extends EventEmitter {
constructor(name) {
this.name = name;
this.browser = null; // Independent browser
this.isRunning = false; // Independent state
this.results = []; // Independent results
}
}

Server broadcasts all events:
// All processors broadcast to the same WebSocket clients
